      <hedline>
        <hl1>The Use of Pesticides</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Letter by Don Eliason (Mosquito and Vector Control Assn of California) says pesticide applications being used by New York City to control West Nile virus have been certified by Environmental Protection Agency and used successfully thoughout country for many years with no evidence of significant harm to humans or environment</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Pesticide Effect, Hard to Assess, Stays in Shadow of Disease Fight'' (news article, July 26):</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''Pesticide Effect, Hard to Assess, Stays in Shadow of Disease Fight'' (news article, July 26):</p>
        <p>People have expressed concern about the potential health and environmental risks of widespread pesticide application related to the West Nile virus, but experience elsewhere demonstrates that these concerns are not justified.</p>
        <p>The materials and methods being used by New York City have been extensively tested, reviewed and certified by the Environmental Protection Agency, and have been used successfully by disease control programs throughout the country for many years with no documented evidence of significant harm to the public or to the environment.</p>
        <p>Mayor Rudolph W. Giuliani's suggestion that there is a trade-off in this case between people and wildlife is overstated.</p>
        <p>DON ELIASON  Exec. Dir., Mosquito and Vector  Control Association of California  Elk Grove, Calif., July 28, 2000</p>
      </block>
    </body.content>
